04971nam a22006615i 9780292743816DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927438167 a10.7560/7438092doi  a(DE-B1597)587437  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHD8108.5.M6 ǂb B56 2012eb 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a331.5441 aBinford, Leigh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTomorrow We're All Going to the Harvest :bTemporary Foreign Worker Programs and Neoliberal Political Economy /cLeigh Binford. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps, Figures, and Tables -- tAcronyms -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Contract Labor Migration in Theory and Practice -- tCHAPTER 1 Agricultural Crisis, Migration, and Contract Labor: Tlaxcala, Mexico, and Ontario, Canada -- tCHAPTER 2 The Dual Process of Constructing Mexican Contract Workers -- tCHAPTER 3 “Tomorrow We’re All Going to the Harvest”: Case Studies of Contract Labor Migration -- tCHAPTER 4 Interrogating Racialized Global Labor Supply: Caribbean and Mexican Workers in Canada’s SAWP -- tCHAPTER 5 The Seasonal Agricultural Worker Program and Mexican Development -- tCHAPTER 6 The Political Economy of Contract Labor in Neoliberal North America: Cheap Labor and Organized Labor -- tCHAPTER 7 Globalization and Temporary Migrants: Post- National Citizens, Realpolitik, and Disposable Labor Power -- tAPPENDIX The SAWP: Saving the Family Farm or Feeding Corporate Enterprise? -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its inception in 1966, the Canadian Seasonal Agricultural Worker Program (SAWP) has grown to employ approximately 20,000 workers annually, the majority from Mexico. The program has been hailed as a model that alleviates human rights concerns because, under contract, SAWP workers travel legally, receive health benefits, contribute to pensions, are represented by Canadian consular officials, and rate the program favorably. Tomorrow We’re All Going to the Harvest takes us behind the ideology and examines the daily lives of SAWP workers from Tlaxcala, Mexico (one of the leading sending states), observing the great personal and family price paid in order to experience a temporary rise in a standard of living. The book also observes the disparities of a gutted Mexican countryside versus the flourishing agriculture in Canada, where farm labor demand remains high. Drawn from extensive surveys and nearly two hundred interviews, ethnographic work in Ontario (destination of over 77 percent of migrants in the author’s sample), and quantitative data, this is much more than a case study; it situates the Tlaxcala-Canada exchange within the broader issues of migration, economics, and cultural currents. Bringing to light the historical genesis of “complementary” labor markets and the contradictory positioning of Mexican government representatives, Leigh Binford also explores the language barriers and nonexistent worker networks in Canada, as well as the physical realities of the work itself, making this book a complete portrait of a provocative segment of migrant labor.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAgricultural laborers, ForeignzCanada. 0aForeign workersxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aForeign workers, MexicanzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aBinford, Leigh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreiBisch, Kerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74380940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn